04472nam a22006975i 9780857453167DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20072007nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808574531677 a10.1515/97808574531672doi  a(DE-B1597)636906  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aSOC0070002bisacsh04a304.8100aGoing First Class? :bNew Approaches to Privileged Travel and Movement /ced. by Vered Amit. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (172 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEASA Series ;v700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1 Structures and Dispositions of Travel and Movement -- t2 Middle-Class Japanese Housewives and the Experience of Transnational Mobility -- t3 Living in a Bubble Expatriates’ Transnational Spaces -- t4 Globalization through “Weak Ties” A Study of Transnational Networks among Mobile Professionals -- t5 Traveling Images, Lives on Location Cinematographers in the Film Industry -- t6 Privileged Travelers? Migration Narratives in Families of Middle-Class Caribbean Background -- t7 How Privileged Are They? Middle-Class Brazilian Immigrants in Lisbon -- t8 Imagined Communitas Older Migrants and Aspirational Mobility -- t9 Privileged Time Volunteers’ Experiences At a Spiritual Educational Retreat Center in Hawai’i -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPeople travel as never before. However, anthropological research has tended to focus primarily on either labor migration or on tourism. In contrast, this collection of essays explores a diversity of circumstances and impetuses towards contemporary mobility. It ranges from expatriates to peripatetic professionals to middle class migrants in search of extended educational and career opportunities to people seeking self development through travel, either by moving after retirement or visiting educational retreats. These situations, however, converge in the significant resources, variously of finances, time, credentials or skills, which these voyagers are able to call on in embarking on their respective journeys. Accordingly, this volume seeks to tease out the scope and implications of the relatively privileged circumstances under which these voyages are being undertaken.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh1 aAmit, Vered, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmit, Vered, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFechter, Meike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenhalgh, Cathy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKurotani, Sawa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOliver, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOlwig, Karen Fog, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRodman, Margaret C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTorresan, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978085745316740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780857453167423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780857453167/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK